      The dewy-eyed and artless young thing who marries Archer. May appears to be unassailably innocent. Over time, Archer comes to see her as the living embodiment of New York society: incapable of thinking on her own, conditioned to act as she is expected. Despite her apparent innocence, May is not as nave as Newland thinks. However, she remains a loyal wife even after she suspects that Newland is having an affair with Countess Olenska.